@thejohnwray asked me to design a “fictional band shirt” in honor of his new novel GONE TO THE WOLVES. I accepted his challenge and tried to channel the artistic skill of the punks and metalheads in my high school art class that I both admired and feared. The book’s publisher is now offering a very limited number of the shirts (as well as ones by @shaptonia and @gary.panter) as a pre-order incentive. Go to @fsgbooks for details.

I was recently asked by Shochiku Co., Ltd. (the distributor of Yasujiro Ozu’s films) to write a brief essay in honor of the 120th anniversary of Ozu’s birth. It was my great honor to write about the first Ozu film I ever saw (OHAYO), and its lasting influence and impact on me. Link in bio.

Here’s the English version of the brief essay mentioned in my previous post. Thanks to Shochiku Co., Ltd. for asking me to be a part of Yasujiro Ozu’s birthday celebration. Link in bio for Japanese version and some great stills.

The first movie I ever saw in New York City was at @angelikafilmny, back when I was a teenage tourist on vacation with his mom. I enjoyed the movie but was also distracted by the rumbling of the subway beneath us. Thirty-three years later I was sitting in that same theater, watching #SHORTCOMINGS with a packed audience, and it was pretty unreal when the room started rumbling and I remembered being there for the first time like it was yesterday.

*Contest ended*

*SHORTCOMINGS CONTEST* In honour of the 8/4 film release of Shortcomings written by Adrian Tomine, directed by Randall Park, we’re giving away limited edition Shortcomings tote bags, with an iconic panel from the graphic novel! To enter, comment below and tag a friend who’ll love Shortcomings. US and CA only, must follow both @adriantomine and @drawnandquarterly. On through July 31st.

I can’t pretend to fully comprehend the intricacies of “clearing” character names in movies—that is, getting the legal right to use a made up name (even if it was the name of the character in a book that’s been in print for fifteen years). But several times during the process of making #SHORTCOMINGS, I was informed that a name did not clear, and that if I wanted any input on the alternate name, I’d have to submit something immediately. So I’d find myself in a situation not unlike that “line of sight” trope from movies where a character has to come up with a name on the spot, and they blurt out something based on whatever they see in front of them. I didn’t name anyone “Cutty” or “Doubtfire,” but close enough. Anyway, here’s a few of my brilliant sources of inspiration.

From 1993 to 2003, I lived in Berkeley on College Ave., just a few blocks away from @rialtocinemaselmwood. I walked by that theater multiple times every day, usually on my way to meet @richardsala_art and @daniel_clowes at Dream Fluff Donuts, or to get a burrito from @gordotaqueria. I wrote the first draft of the SHORTCOMINGS graphic novel during that time, and the Elmwood Theater (along with the California on Kittredge) was a big inspiration for the fictional “Berkeley Arts Cinema.” So much has changed since then, and it nearly brings me to tears to know that this story has ended up where it began.

Every day that I was on set, I noticed things like this: evidence of someone from our ingenious, tireless crew putting thought and care into something that was appropriate and enriching to the story, but that might not even appear on screen at all. I think there’s a cumulative effect that comes from this kind of detail, and at very least, it was never lost on me. More to follow in upcoming posts. #shortcomings

💐 Spring 2024 Announcements 💐

Next up is Shortcomings: A Screenplay by Adrian Tomine!

The major motion picture adaptation of Adrian Tomine’s beloved New York Times Notable Book debuted at the Sundance Film Festival and made its New York premiere at the Tribeca Festival to great acclaim. 

Written by Tomine and helmed by director Randall Park, Shortcomings was lauded by The New York Times for its liberating representation of Asian Americans in all their messiness and humanity.

Tomine’s screenplay is presented here in its final “shooting draft” form, along with extensive annotations, commentary, and bonuses including deleted and alternate scenes. This gorgeously-designed volume is supplemented with film stills, behind-the-scenes photos, and also includes an introduction by Park and a new, original comic from Tomine.

More announcements to come!
